@@ -0,0 +1,291 @@
+# Matrix Bridge Operations
+
+This runbook governs the production lifecycle of the Signal, Telegram, and
+WhatsApp Matrix bridges. Repository preparation and live operations remain
+separate: changes are reviewed and merged first; Lydia or the operator performs
+deployment afterward.
+
+## Preconditions And Safety
+
+- Record `<release-commit>`, `<previous-release-commit>`, and `<backup-timestamp>`
+  before any mutation.
+- Obtain explicit operator authorization for deployment, account linking,
+  credential rotation, restore, or rollback.
+- Run one bridge change at a time. Signal and Telegram are mandatory regression
+  gates while WhatsApp is changed.
+- Keep config files, registrations, database dumps, and persistent state outside
+  Git with mode `0600` inside directories with mode `0700`.
+- Never paste raw logs, config files, registrations, database output, cookies,
+  tokens, QR codes, or session data into issues, pull requests, or chat.
+- Compare generated appservice token consistency locally using SHA-256 hashes
+  only. Record that hashes match, never the values.
+
+| Bridge | Persistent state | Database | Synapse registration |
+|---|---|---|---|
+| mautrix-signal | `/home/michael/mautrix-signal` | `mautrix_signal` | `/data/appservice/mautrix-signal.yaml` |
+| mautrix-telegram | `/home/michael/mautrix-telegram` | `mautrix_telegram` | `/data/appservice/mautrix-telegram.yaml` |
+| mautrix-whatsapp | `/home/michael/mautrix-whatsapp` | `mautrix_whatsapp` | `/data/appservice/mautrix-whatsapp.yaml` |
+
+Before deployment, confirm the versioned Compose file renders, the image is
+digest-pinned for `linux/arm64`, the service joins only `bridge_internal`, and
+resolved host port bindings are empty.
+
+## Start And Stop
+
+Use Compose directly from the clean, detached Architecture checkout. A runtime
+copy under `/home/michael/matrix/compose` is not release evidence and must not be
+used by this procedure:
+
+```bash
+ARCHITECTURE_ROOT="<architecture-checkout>"
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" fetch origin
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" switch --detach <release-commit>
+test "$(git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" rev-parse HEAD)" = "<release-commit>"
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" diff --quiet
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" diff --cached --quiet
+
+COMPOSE_FILE="$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT/pi/compose/mautrix-<bridge>.yml"
+test -f "$COMPOSE_FILE"
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" diff --quiet <release-commit> -- \
+  "pi/compose/mautrix-<bridge>.yml"
+docker compose -f "$COMPOSE_FILE" config -q
+docker compose -f "$COMPOSE_FILE" up -d
+docker compose -f "$COMPOSE_FILE" stop
+```
+
+The detached commit, clean-worktree check, repository-relative file path, and
+Compose command form one release binding. Record the commit and SHA-256 of
+`$COMPOSE_FILE` as deployment evidence. Apply the same checks to
+`pi/compose/synapse.yml`, `pi/synapse/entrypoint.sh`, and
+`pi/synapse/synapse.yaml.example` before a Synapse appservice-list change.
+
+Start order is PostgreSQL, Synapse, then one bridge. Stop order is the selected
+bridge first; do not stop unrelated bridges. After changing Synapse appservice
+configuration, verify that existing registrations remain listed before
+recreating Synapse.
+
+## Health And Regression Gates
+
+For the selected container, verify both bridge endpoints from a container on
+`bridge_internal`:
+
+```text
+http://mautrix-<bridge>:<port>/_matrix/mau/live
+http://mautrix-<bridge>:<port>/_matrix/mau/ready
+```
+
+Both `/_matrix/mau/live` and `/_matrix/mau/ready` must return HTTP 200. Then
+verify container state, isolation, database connectivity, and active Synapse
+registrations:
+
+```bash
+docker inspect <container> --format '{{json .State}}'
+docker inspect <container> --format '{{json .HostConfig.PortBindings}}'
+docker inspect <container> --format '{{json .NetworkSettings.Networks}}'
+docker stats --no-stream <container>
+```
+
+The port-binding result must be empty and only `bridge_internal` is allowed.
+Record CPU, RSS, Swap, and Storage before and after a new bridge is introduced.
+The active Synapse config must retain every deployed path:
+
+```text
+/data/appservice/mautrix-signal.yaml
+/data/appservice/mautrix-telegram.yaml
+/data/appservice/mautrix-whatsapp.yaml
+```
+
+Signal and Telegram liveness, readiness, bot response, and Synapse client/SSO
+behavior must remain unchanged after a WhatsApp deployment.
+
+## Safe Log Diagnosis
+
+Inspect logs locally and report only bounded counts and time ranges. This
+example emits a count, not matching lines:
+
+```bash
+docker logs --since 10m <container> 2>&1 \
+  | grep -ciE 'appservice|database|network|fatal|panic|permission denied'
+```
+
+Never paste raw logs as evidence. If diagnosis requires content, redact it on
+the host before sharing and exclude authorization headers, Matrix IDs, phone
+numbers, cookies, QR data, tokens, connection strings, and message content.
+
+## Backup
+
+Create a restricted backup before every deployment, upgrade, registration
+change, restore test, or credential rotation:
+
+```bash
+umask 077
+BACKUP_DIR="/mnt/hardDrive/backups/matrix-bridges/<backup-timestamp>"
+mkdir -p "$BACKUP_DIR/databases" "$BACKUP_DIR/state" \
+  "$BACKUP_DIR/appservice" "$BACKUP_DIR/synapse"
+chmod 700 "$BACKUP_DIR"
+```
+
+Capture the active Synapse configuration, its appservice list, and the exact
+versioned template before changing registrations. The rendered config contains
+secrets and receives the same restricted handling as registrations:
+
+```bash
+docker cp compose-synapse-1:/run/synapse/homeserver.yaml \
+  "$BACKUP_DIR/synapse/homeserver.active.yaml"
+cp "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT/pi/synapse/synapse.yaml.example" \
+  "$BACKUP_DIR/synapse/synapse.yaml.example"
+docker exec compose-synapse-1 python3 -c \
+  'import json,yaml; c=yaml.safe_load(open("/run/synapse/homeserver.yaml")); print(json.dumps(c.get("app_service_config_files", []), sort_keys=True))' \
+  > "$BACKUP_DIR/synapse/app_service_config_files.json"
+```
+
+Stop one bridge, dump its dedicated database, archive its persistent state, and
+copy its registration. Then restart it and pass its health gates before
+selecting the next bridge. Repeat for `signal`, `telegram`, and `whatsapp` when
+present:
+
+```bash
+COMPOSE_FILE="$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT/pi/compose/mautrix-<bridge>.yml"
+docker compose -f "$COMPOSE_FILE" stop
+docker exec compose-postgres-1 pg_dump -U mautrix_<bridge> \
+  -d mautrix_<bridge> -Fc > "$BACKUP_DIR/databases/mautrix_<bridge>.dump"
+tar -C /home/michael -czf "$BACKUP_DIR/state/mautrix-<bridge>.tar.gz" \
+  mautrix-<bridge>
+cp "/mnt/hardDrive/docker/synapse/data/appservice/mautrix-<bridge>.yaml" \
+  "$BACKUP_DIR/appservice/"
+docker compose -f "$COMPOSE_FILE" up -d
+# Require /_matrix/mau/live and /_matrix/mau/ready HTTP 200 before continuing.
+```
+
+Registration copies and state archives contain secrets. Keep them local with
+restricted permissions. Add a manifest containing only release commits, image
+digests, bridge names, database names, and timestamps. Generate and verify
+checksums without printing file contents:
+
+```bash
+(cd "$BACKUP_DIR" && find . -type f ! -name sha256sums.txt -exec sha256sum {} \; > sha256sums.txt)
+(cd "$BACKUP_DIR" && sha256sum -c sha256sums.txt)
+```
+
+The backup is incomplete if any selected bridge cannot restart and pass its
+health gates, if the active Synapse list cannot be parsed, or if checksums fail.
+
+## Restore
+
+Restore into an isolated maintenance window. Verify checksums, stop the target
+bridge, and retain the failed state until recovery is accepted:
+
+```bash
+cd "/mnt/hardDrive/backups/matrix-bridges/<backup-timestamp>"
+sha256sum -c sha256sums.txt
+ARCHITECTURE_ROOT="<architecture-checkout>"
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" switch --detach <release-commit>
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" diff --quiet
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" diff --cached --quiet
+COMPOSE_FILE="$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT/pi/compose/mautrix-<bridge>.yml"
+docker compose -f "$COMPOSE_FILE" stop
+```
+
+Restore the persistent archive, registration, and dedicated database with their
+original ownership and restrictive permissions. The database restore contract
+is:
+
+```bash
+docker exec -i compose-postgres-1 pg_restore --clean --if-exists \
+  -U mautrix_<bridge> -d mautrix_<bridge> \
+  < "databases/mautrix_<bridge>.dump"
+```
+
+Copy the selected registration back to the Synapse appservice directory without
+removing existing registrations. Verify its bot and ghost namespaces locally,
+and verify the checked-out `pi/synapse/synapse.yaml.example` matches the backed-up
+template. Do not copy the rendered `homeserver.active.yaml` into Git or the
+container; it is restricted recovery evidence because the entrypoint regenerates
+the active tmpfs file from the versioned template and runtime secrets.
+
+```bash
+cd "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT"
+cmp pi/synapse/synapse.yaml.example \
+  "$BACKUP_DIR/synapse/synapse.yaml.example"
+```
+
+If the registration set changed, bind `SYNAPSE_COMPOSE` to the same reviewed
+checkout and recreate Synapse:
+
+```bash
+SYNAPSE_COMPOSE="$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT/pi/compose/synapse.yml"
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" diff --quiet <release-commit> -- \
+  pi/compose/synapse.yml pi/synapse/entrypoint.sh \
+  pi/synapse/synapse.yaml.example
+docker compose -f "$SYNAPSE_COMPOSE" up -d --force-recreate synapse
+```
+
+Extract the new active `app_service_config_files` list and compare it byte for
+byte with `synapse/app_service_config_files.json`. The restore passes only when
+the reverted list matches the previous release and all pre-existing
+registrations are preserved. Start the target bridge, then run health,
+regression, and operator blackbox checks.
+
+## Upgrade
+
+1. Create one Architecture branch and PR for one bridge image/config upgrade.
+2. Pin the new multi-arch manifest digest and verify its ARM64 descriptor.
+3. Generate a candidate config and registration from that exact image in an
+   isolated staging directory. Never overwrite production during generation.
+4. Compare schema and namespace changes without displaying secret values.
+   Verify config/registration token consistency using hashes only.
+5. Register contract tests in `ci-manifest.yaml`; require green PR CI and review.
+6. After merge, fetch and detach `<release-commit>`, prove the checkout is clean,
+   bind Compose to the repository path, create a complete backup, and let Lydia
+   or the operator deploy only those reviewed files.
+7. Start only the upgraded bridge. Require its health gates and all existing
+   bridge regression gates before acceptance.
+
+Do not use floating tags. A generated registration must preserve unique bot and
+ghost namespaces and must not replace unrelated appservices.
+
+## Rollback
+
+Abort on failed health, namespace collision, database migration failure, rising
+Swap, or regression in Synapse or another bridge. Stop the changed bridge and
+return to the reviewed prior release:
+
+```bash
+ARCHITECTURE_ROOT="<architecture-checkout>"
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" switch --detach <previous-release-commit>
+test "$(git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" rev-parse HEAD)" = \
+  "<previous-release-commit>"
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" diff --quiet
+git -C "$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT" diff --cached --quiet
+COMPOSE_FILE="$ARCHITECTURE_ROOT/pi/compose/mautrix-<bridge>.yml"
+docker compose -f "$COMPOSE_FILE" stop
+```
+
+Restore the pre-change database, state archive, and registration from
+`<backup-timestamp>`, then recreate the prior bridge container directly from the
+previous checkout. If Synapse's registration list changed, use the previous
+checkout's `pi/compose/synapse.yml` and `pi/synapse/synapse.yaml.example` to
+regenerate the active config, then compare its appservice list to the backed-up
+`app_service_config_files.json`. Run the full health and regression gates;
+preserve failed-upgrade evidence without raw runtime content.
+
+## Operator Blackbox Test
+
+Action: Open a private Matrix room with the selected bridge bot and request its
+help or status command.
+
+Expected: The bot responds without appservice, database, or network errors.
+
+Evidence: Record timestamp, bridge name, pass/fail, and redacted response type;
+do not record message content, IDs, QR data, or credentials.
+
+Action: For Signal use `login` and scan the QR in Signal Linked Devices. For
+WhatsApp use `login` and scan the QR in WhatsApp Linked Devices. For Telegram,
+use the documented interactive login only after runtime API credentials exist.
+
+Expected: The account is linked as the intended device/session and one test
+message crosses the bridge in each direction.
+
+Evidence: Record only pass/fail and timestamps. Abort on account-registration
+prompts, unexpected phone-number takeover, checkpoint loops, or another bridge
+failing its regression gate.
